3254
3255void ata_timing_merge(const struct ata_timing *a, const struct ata_timing *b,
3256 struct ata_timing *m, unsigned int what)
3257{
3258 if (what & ATA_TIMING_SETUP ) m->setup = max(a->setup, b->setup);
3259 if (what & ATA_TIMING_ACT8B ) m->act8b = max(a->act8b, b->act8b);
3260 if (what & ATA_TIMING_REC8B ) m->rec8b = max(a->rec8b, b->rec8b);
3261 if (what & ATA_TIMING_CYC8B ) m->cyc8b = max(a->cyc8b, b->cyc8b);
3262 if (what & ATA_TIMING_ACTIVE ) m->active = max(a->active, b->active);
3263 if (what & ATA_TIMING_RECOVER) m->recover = max(a->recover, b->recover);
3264 if (what & ATA_TIMING_DMACK_HOLD) m->dmack_hold = max(a->dmack_hold, b->dmack_hold);
3265 if (what & ATA_TIMING_CYCLE ) m->cycle = max(a->cycle, b->cycle);
3266 if (what & ATA_TIMING_UDMA ) m->udma = max(a->udma, b->udma);
3267}
3268
3269const struct ata_timing *ata_timing_find_mode(u8 xfer_mode)
3270{
3271 const struct ata_timing *t = ata_timing;
3272
3273 while (xfer_mode > t->mode)
3274 t++;
3275
3276 if (xfer_mode == t->mode)
3277 return t;
3278
3279 WARN_ONCE(true, "%s: unable to find timing for xfer_mode 0x%x\n",
3280 __func__, xfer_mode);
3281
3282 return NULL;
3283}
3284
3285int ata_timing_compute(struct ata_device *adev, unsigned short speed,
3286 struct ata_timing *t, int T, int UT)
3287{
3288 const u16 *id = adev->id;
3289 const struct ata_timing *s;
3290 struct ata_timing p;
3291
3292 /*
3293 * Find the mode.
3294 */
3295
3296 if (!(s = ata_timing_find_mode(speed)))
3297 return -EINVAL;
3298
3299 memcpy(t, s, sizeof(*s));
3300
3301 /*
3302 * If the drive is an EIDE drive, it can tell us it needs extended
3303 * PIO/MW_DMA cycle timing.
3304 */
3305
3306 if (id[ATA_ID_FIELD_VALID] & 2) { /* EIDE drive */
3307 memset(&p, 0, sizeof(p));
3308
3309 if (speed >= XFER_PIO_0 && speed < XFER_SW_DMA_0) {
3310 if (speed <= XFER_PIO_2)
3311 p.cycle = p.cyc8b = id[ATA_ID_EIDE_PIO];
3312 else if ((speed <= XFER_PIO_4) ||
3313 (speed == XFER_PIO_5 && !ata_id_is_cfa(id)))
3314 p.cycle = p.cyc8b = id[ATA_ID_EIDE_PIO_IORDY];
3315 } else if (speed >= XFER_MW_DMA_0 && speed <= XFER_MW_DMA_2)
3316 p.cycle = id[ATA_ID_EIDE_DMA_MIN];
3317
3318 ata_timing_merge(&p, t, t, ATA_TIMING_CYCLE | ATA_TIMING_CYC8B);
3319 }
3320
3321 /*
3322 * Convert the timing to bus clock counts.
3323 */
3324
3325 ata_timing_quantize(t, t, T, UT);
3326
3327 /*
3328 * Even in DMA/UDMA modes we still use PIO access for IDENTIFY,
3329 * S.M.A.R.T * and some other commands. We have to ensure that the
3330 * DMA cycle timing is slower/equal than the fastest PIO timing.
3331 */
3332
3333 if (speed > XFER_PIO_6) {
3334 ata_timing_compute(adev, adev->pio_mode, &p, T, UT);
3335 ata_timing_merge(&p, t, t, ATA_TIMING_ALL);
3336 }
3337
3338 /*
3339 * Lengthen active & recovery time so that cycle time is correct.
3340 */
3341
3342 if (t->act8b + t->rec8b < t->cyc8b) {
3343 t->act8b += (t->cyc8b - (t->act8b + t->rec8b)) / 2;
3344 t->rec8b = t->cyc8b - t->act8b;
3345 }
3346
3347 if (t->active + t->recover < t->cycle) {
3348 t->active += (t->cycle - (t->active + t->recover)) / 2;
3349 t->recover = t->cycle - t->active;
3350 }
3351
3352 /* In a few cases quantisation may produce enough errors to
3353 leave t->cycle too low for the sum of active and recovery
3354 if so we must correct this */
3355 if (t->active + t->recover > t->cycle)
3356 t->cycle = t->active + t->recover;
3357
3358 return 0;
3359}
3360
3361/**
3362 * ata_timing_cycle2mode - find xfer mode for the specified cycle duration
3363 * @xfer_shift: ATA_SHIFT_* value for transfer type to examine.
3364 * @cycle: cycle duration in ns
3365 *
3366 * Return matching xfer mode for @cycle. The returned mode is of
3367 * the transfer type specified by @xfer_shift. If @cycle is too
3368 * slow for @xfer_shift, 0xff is returned. If @cycle is faster
3369 * than the fastest known mode, the fasted mode is returned.
3370 *
3371 * LOCKING:
3372 * None.
3373 *
3374 * RETURNS:
3375 * Matching xfer_mode, 0xff if no match found.
3376 */
3377u8 ata_timing_cycle2mode(unsigned int xfer_shift, int cycle)
3378{
3379 u8 base_mode = 0xff, last_mode = 0xff;
3380 const struct ata_xfer_ent *ent;
3381 const struct ata_timing *t;
3382
3383 for (ent = ata_xfer_tbl; ent->shift >= 0; ent++)
3384 if (ent->shift == xfer_shift)
3385 base_mode = ent->base;
3386
3387 for (t = ata_timing_find_mode(base_mode);
3388 t && ata_xfer_mode2shift(t->mode) == xfer_shift; t++) {
3389 unsigned short this_cycle;
3390
3391 switch (xfer_shift) {
3392 case ATA_SHIFT_PIO:
3393 case ATA_SHIFT_MWDMA:
3394 this_cycle = t->cycle;
3395 break;
3396 case ATA_SHIFT_UDMA:
3397 this_cycle = t->udma;
3398 break;
3399 default:
3400 return 0xff;
3401 }
3402
3403 if (cycle > this_cycle)
3404 break;
3405
3406 last_mode = t->mode;
3407 }
3408
3409 return last_mode;
3410}

3412/**
3413 * ata_down_xfermask_limit - adjust dev xfer masks downward
3414 * @dev: Device to adjust xfer masks
3415 * @sel: ATA_DNXFER_* selector
3416 *
3417 * Adjust xfer masks of @dev downward. Note that this function
3418 * does not apply the change. Invoking ata_set_mode() afterwards
3419 * will apply the limit.
3420 *
3421 * LOCKING:
3422 * Inherited from caller.
3423 *
3424 * RETURNS:
3425 * 0 on success, negative errno on failure
3426 */
3427int ata_down_xfermask_limit(struct ata_device *dev, unsigned int sel)
3428{
3429 char buf[32];
3430 unsigned long orig_mask, xfer_mask;
3431 unsigned long pio_mask, mwdma_mask, udma_mask;
3432 int quiet, highbit;
3433
3434 quiet = !!(sel & ATA_DNXFER_QUIET);
3435 sel &= ~ATA_DNXFER_QUIET;
3436
3437 xfer_mask = orig_mask = ata_pack_xfermask(dev->pio_mask,
3438 dev->mwdma_mask,
3439 dev->udma_mask);
3440 ata_unpack_xfermask(xfer_mask, &pio_mask, &mwdma_mask, &udma_mask);
3441
3442 switch (sel) {
3443 case ATA_DNXFER_PIO:
3444 highbit = fls(pio_mask) - 1;
3445 pio_mask &= ~(1 << highbit);
3446 break;
3447
3448 case ATA_DNXFER_DMA:
3449 if (udma_mask) {
3450 highbit = fls(udma_mask) - 1;
3451 udma_mask &= ~(1 << highbit);
3452 if (!udma_mask)
3453 return -ENOENT;
3454 } else if (mwdma_mask) {
3455 highbit = fls(mwdma_mask) - 1;
3456 mwdma_mask &= ~(1 << highbit);
3457 if (!mwdma_mask)
3458 return -ENOENT;
3459 }
3460 break;
3461
3462 case ATA_DNXFER_40C:
3463 udma_mask &= ATA_UDMA_MASK_40C;
3464 break;
3465
3466 case ATA_DNXFER_FORCE_PIO0:
3467 pio_mask &= 1;
3468 case ATA_DNXFER_FORCE_PIO:
3469 mwdma_mask = 0;
3470 udma_mask = 0;
3471 break;
3472
3473 default:
3474 BUG();
3475 }
3476
3477 xfer_mask &= ata_pack_xfermask(pio_mask, mwdma_mask, udma_mask);
3478
3479 if (!(xfer_mask & ATA_MASK_PIO) || xfer_mask == orig_mask)
3480 return -ENOENT;
3481
3482 if (!quiet) {
3483 if (xfer_mask & (ATA_MASK_MWDMA | ATA_MASK_UDMA))
3484 snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "%s:%s",
3485 ata_mode_string(xfer_mask),
3486 ata_mode_string(xfer_mask & ATA_MASK_PIO));
3487 else
3488 snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "%s",
3489 ata_mode_string(xfer_mask));
3490
3491 ata_dev_warn(dev, "limiting speed to %s\n", buf);
3492 }
3493
3494 ata_unpack_xfermask(xfer_mask, &dev->pio_mask, &dev->mwdma_mask,
3495 &dev->udma_mask);
3496
3497 return 0;
3498}
3499
3500static int ata_dev_set_mode(struct ata_device *dev)
3501{
3502 struct ata_port *ap = dev->link->ap;
3503 struct ata_eh_context *ehc = &dev->link->eh_context;
3504 const bool nosetxfer = dev->horkage & ATA_HORKAGE_NOSETXFER;
3505 const char *dev_err_whine = "";
3506 int ign_dev_err = 0;
3507 unsigned int err_mask = 0;
3508 int rc;
3509
3510 dev->flags &= ~ATA_DFLAG_PIO;
3511 if (dev->xfer_shift == ATA_SHIFT_PIO)
3512 dev->flags |= ATA_DFLAG_PIO;
3513
3514 if (nosetxfer && ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_SATA && ata_id_is_sata(dev->id))
3515 dev_err_whine = " (SET_XFERMODE skipped)";
3516 else {
3517 if (nosetxfer)
3518 ata_dev_warn(dev,
3519 "NOSETXFER but PATA detected - can't "
3520 "skip SETXFER, might malfunction\n");
3521 err_mask = ata_dev_set_xfermode(dev);
3522 }
3523
3524 if (err_mask & ~AC_ERR_DEV)
3525 goto fail;
3526
3527 /* revalidate */
3528 ehc->i.flags |= ATA_EHI_POST_SETMODE;
3529 rc = ata_dev_revalidate(dev, ATA_DEV_UNKNOWN, 0);
3530 ehc->i.flags &= ~ATA_EHI_POST_SETMODE;
3531 if (rc)
3532 return rc;
3533
3534 if (dev->xfer_shift == ATA_SHIFT_PIO) {
3535 /* Old CFA may refuse this command, which is just fine */
3536 if (ata_id_is_cfa(dev->id))
3537 ign_dev_err = 1;
3538 /* Catch several broken garbage emulations plus some pre
3539 ATA devices */
3540 if (ata_id_major_version(dev->id) == 0 &&
3541 dev->pio_mode <= XFER_PIO_2)
3542 ign_dev_err = 1;
3543 /* Some very old devices and some bad newer ones fail
3544 any kind of SET_XFERMODE request but support PIO0-2
3545 timings and no IORDY */
3546 if (!ata_id_has_iordy(dev->id) && dev->pio_mode <= XFER_PIO_2)
3547 ign_dev_err = 1;
3548 }
3549 /* Early MWDMA devices do DMA but don't allow DMA mode setting.
3550 Don't fail an MWDMA0 set IFF the device indicates it is in MWDMA0 */
3551 if (dev->xfer_shift == ATA_SHIFT_MWDMA &&
3552 dev->dma_mode == XFER_MW_DMA_0 &&
3553 (dev->id[63] >> 8) & 1)
3554 ign_dev_err = 1;
3555
3556 /* if the device is actually configured correctly, ignore dev err */
3557 if (dev->xfer_mode == ata_xfer_mask2mode(ata_id_xfermask(dev->id)))
3558 ign_dev_err = 1;
3559
3560 if (err_mask & AC_ERR_DEV) {
3561 if (!ign_dev_err)
3562 goto fail;
3563 else
3564 dev_err_whine = " (device error ignored)";
3565 }
3566
3567 DPRINTK("xfer_shift=%u, xfer_mode=0x%x\n",
3568 dev->xfer_shift, (int)dev->xfer_mode);
3569
3570 ata_dev_info(dev, "configured for %s%s\n",
3571 ata_mode_string(ata_xfer_mode2mask(dev->xfer_mode)),
3572 dev_err_whine);
3573
3574 return 0;
3575
3576 fail:
3577 ata_dev_err(dev, "failed to set xfermode (err_mask=0x%x)\n", err_mask);
3578 return -EIO;
3579}
3580
3581/**
3582 * ata_do_set_mode - Program timings and issue SET FEATURES - XFER
3583 * @link: link on which timings will be programmed
3584 * @r_failed_dev: out parameter for failed device
3585 *
3586 * Standard implementation of the function used to tune and set
3587 * ATA device disk transfer mode (PIO3, UDMA6, etc.). If
3588 * ata_dev_set_mode() fails, pointer to the failing device is
3589 * returned in @r_failed_dev.
3590 *
3591 * LOCKING:
3592 * PCI/etc. bus probe sem.
3593 *
3594 * RETURNS:
3595 * 0 on success, negative errno otherwise
3596 */
3597
3598int ata_do_set_mode(struct ata_link *link, struct ata_device **r_failed_dev)
3599{
3600 struct ata_port *ap = link->ap;
3601 struct ata_device *dev;
3602 int rc = 0, used_dma = 0, found = 0;
3603
3604 /* step 1: calculate xfer_mask */
3605 ata_for_each_dev(dev, link, ENABLED) {
3606 unsigned long pio_mask, dma_mask;
3607 unsigned int mode_mask;
3608
3609 mode_mask = ATA_DMA_MASK_ATA;
3610 if (dev->class == ATA_DEV_ATAPI)
3611 mode_mask = ATA_DMA_MASK_ATAPI;
3612 else if (ata_id_is_cfa(dev->id))
3613 mode_mask = ATA_DMA_MASK_CFA;
3614
3615 ata_dev_xfermask(dev);
3616 ata_force_xfermask(dev);
3617
3618 pio_mask = ata_pack_xfermask(dev->pio_mask, 0, 0);
3619
3620 if (libata_dma_mask & mode_mask)
3621 dma_mask = ata_pack_xfermask(0, dev->mwdma_mask,
3622 dev->udma_mask);
3623 else
3624 dma_mask = 0;
3625
3626 dev->pio_mode = ata_xfer_mask2mode(pio_mask);
3627 dev->dma_mode = ata_xfer_mask2mode(dma_mask);
3628
3629 found = 1;
3630 if (ata_dma_enabled(dev))
3631 used_dma = 1;
3632 }
3633 if (!found)
3634 goto out;
3635
3636 /* step 2: always set host PIO timings */
3637 ata_for_each_dev(dev, link, ENABLED) {
3638 if (dev->pio_mode == 0xff) {
3639 ata_dev_warn(dev, "no PIO support\n");
3640 rc = -EINVAL;
3641 goto out;
3642 }
3643
3644 dev->xfer_mode = dev->pio_mode;
3645 dev->xfer_shift = ATA_SHIFT_PIO;
3646 if (ap->ops->set_piomode)
3647 ap->ops->set_piomode(ap, dev);
3648 }
3649
3650 /* step 3: set host DMA timings */
3651 ata_for_each_dev(dev, link, ENABLED) {
3652 if (!ata_dma_enabled(dev))
3653 continue;
3654
3655 dev->xfer_mode = dev->dma_mode;
3656 dev->xfer_shift = ata_xfer_mode2shift(dev->dma_mode);
3657 if (ap->ops->set_dmamode)
3658 ap->ops->set_dmamode(ap, dev);
3659 }
3660
3661 /* step 4: update devices' xfer mode */
3662 ata_for_each_dev(dev, link, ENABLED) {
3663 rc = ata_dev_set_mode(dev);
3664 if (rc)
3665 goto out;
3666 }
3667
3668 /* Record simplex status. If we selected DMA then the other
3669 * host channels are not permitted to do so.
3670 */
3671 if (used_dma && (ap->host->flags & ATA_HOST_SIMPLEX))
3672 ap->host->simplex_claimed = ap;
3673
3674 out:
3675 if (rc)
3676 *r_failed_dev = dev;
3677 return rc;
3678}
3679
3680/**
3681 * ata_wait_ready - wait for link to become ready
3682 * @link: link to be waited on
3683 * @deadline: deadline jiffies for the operation
3684 * @check_ready: callback to check link readiness
3685 *
3686 * Wait for @link to become ready. @check_ready should return
3687 * positive number if @link is ready, 0 if it isn't, -ENODEV if
3688 * link doesn't seem to be occupied, other errno for other error
3689 * conditions.
3690 *
3691 * Transient -ENODEV conditions are allowed for
3692 * ATA_TMOUT_FF_WAIT.
3693 *
3694 * LOCKING:
3695 * EH context.
3696 *
3697 * RETURNS:
3698 * 0 if @link is ready before @deadline; otherwise, -errno.
3699 */
3700int ata_wait_ready(struct ata_link *link, unsigned long deadline,
3701 int (*check_ready)(struct ata_link *link))
3702{
3703 unsigned long start = jiffies;
3704 unsigned long nodev_deadline;
3705 int warned = 0;
3706
3707 /* choose which 0xff timeout to use, read comment in libata.h */
3708 if (link->ap->host->flags & ATA_HOST_PARALLEL_SCAN)
3709 nodev_deadline = ata_deadline(start, ATA_TMOUT_FF_WAIT_LONG);
3710 else
3711 nodev_deadline = ata_deadline(start, ATA_TMOUT_FF_WAIT);
3712
3713 /* Slave readiness can't be tested separately from master. On
3714 * M/S emulation configuration, this function should be called
3715 * only on the master and it will handle both master and slave.
3716 */
3717 WARN_ON(link == link->ap->slave_link);
3718
3719 if (time_after(nodev_deadline, deadline))
3720 nodev_deadline = deadline;
3721
3722 while (1) {
3723 unsigned long now = jiffies;
3724 int ready, tmp;
3725
3726 ready = tmp = check_ready(link);
3727 if (ready > 0)
3728 return 0;
3729
3730 /*
3731 * -ENODEV could be transient. Ignore -ENODEV if link
3732 * is online. Also, some SATA devices take a long
3733 * time to clear 0xff after reset. Wait for
3734 * ATA_TMOUT_FF_WAIT[_LONG] on -ENODEV if link isn't
3735 * offline.
3736 *
3737 * Note that some PATA controllers (pata_ali) explode
3738 * if status register is read more than once when
3739 * there's no device attached.
3740 */
3741 if (ready == -ENODEV) {
3742 if (ata_link_online(link))
3743 ready = 0;
3744 else if ((link->ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_SATA) &&
3745 !ata_link_offline(link) &&
3746 time_before(now, nodev_deadline))
3747 ready = 0;
3748 }
3749
3750 if (ready)
3751 return ready;
3752 if (time_after(now, deadline))
3753 return -EBUSY;
3754
3755 if (!warned && time_after(now, start + 5 * HZ) &&
3756 (deadline - now > 3 * HZ)) {
3757 ata_link_warn(link,
3758 "link is slow to respond, please be patient "
3759 "(ready=%d)\n", tmp);
3760 warned = 1;
3761 }
3762
3763 ata_msleep(link->ap, 50);
3764 }
3765}
3766
3767/**
3768 * ata_wait_after_reset - wait for link to become ready after reset
3769 * @link: link to be waited on
3770 * @deadline: deadline jiffies for the operation
3771 * @check_ready: callback to check link readiness
3772 *
3773 * Wait for @link to become ready after reset.
3774 *
3775 * LOCKING:
3776 * EH context.
3777 *
3778 * RETURNS:
3779 * 0 if @link is ready before @deadline; otherwise, -errno.
3780 */
3781int ata_wait_after_reset(struct ata_link *link, unsigned long deadline,
3782 int (*check_ready)(struct ata_link *link))
3783{
3784 ata_msleep(link->ap, ATA_WAIT_AFTER_RESET);
3785
3786 return ata_wait_ready(link, deadline, check_ready);
3787}

3789/**
3790 * sata_link_debounce - debounce SATA phy status
3791 * @link: ATA link to debounce SATA phy status for
3792 * @params: timing parameters { interval, duration, timeout } in msec
3793 * @deadline: deadline jiffies for the operation
3794 *
3795 * Make sure SStatus of @link reaches stable state, determined by
3796 * holding the same value where DET is not 1 for @duration polled
3797 * every @interval, before @timeout. Timeout constraints the
3798 * beginning of the stable state. Because DET gets stuck at 1 on
3799 * some controllers after hot unplugging, this functions waits
3800 * until timeout then returns 0 if DET is stable at 1.
3801 *
3802 * @timeout is further limited by @deadline. The sooner of the
3803 * two is used.
3804 *
3805 * LOCKING:
3806 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
3807 *
3808 * RETURNS:
3809 * 0 on success, -errno on failure.
3810 */
3811int sata_link_debounce(struct ata_link *link, const unsigned long *params,
3812 unsigned long deadline)
3813{
3814 unsigned long interval = params[0];
3815 unsigned long duration = params[1];
3816 unsigned long last_jiffies, t;
3817 u32 last, cur;
3818 int rc;
3819
3820 t = ata_deadline(jiffies, params[2]);
3821 if (time_before(t, deadline))
3822 deadline = t;
3823
3824 if ((rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_STATUS, &cur)))
3825 return rc;
3826 cur &= 0xf;
3827
3828 last = cur;
3829 last_jiffies = jiffies;
3830
3831 while (1) {
3832 ata_msleep(link->ap, interval);
3833 if ((rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_STATUS, &cur)))
3834 return rc;
3835 cur &= 0xf;
3836
3837 /* DET stable? */
3838 if (cur == last) {
3839 if (cur == 1 && time_before(jiffies, deadline))
3840 continue;
3841 if (time_after(jiffies,
3842 ata_deadline(last_jiffies, duration)))
3843 return 0;
3844 continue;
3845 }
3846
3847 /* unstable, start over */
3848 last = cur;
3849 last_jiffies = jiffies;
3850
3851 /* Check deadline. If debouncing failed, return
3852 * -EPIPE to tell upper layer to lower link speed.
3853 */
3854 if (time_after(jiffies, deadline))
3855 return -EPIPE;
3856 }
3857}
3858
3859/**
3860 * sata_link_resume - resume SATA link
3861 * @link: ATA link to resume SATA
3862 * @params: timing parameters { interval, duration, timeout } in msec
3863 * @deadline: deadline jiffies for the operation
3864 *
3865 * Resume SATA phy @link and debounce it.
3866 *
3867 * LOCKING:
3868 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
3869 *
3870 * RETURNS:
3871 * 0 on success, -errno on failure.
3872 */
3873int sata_link_resume(struct ata_link *link, const unsigned long *params,
3874 unsigned long deadline)
3875{
3876 int tries = ATA_LINK_RESUME_TRIES;
3877 u32 scontrol, serror;
3878 int rc;
3879
3880 if ((rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_CONTROL, &scontrol)))
3881 return rc;
3882
3883 /*
3884 * Writes to SControl sometimes get ignored under certain
3885 * controllers (ata_piix SIDPR). Make sure DET actually is
3886 * cleared.
3887 */
3888 do {
3889 scontrol = (scontrol & 0x0f0) | 0x300;
3890 if ((rc = sata_scr_write(link, SCR_CONTROL, scontrol)))
3891 return rc;
3892 /*
3893 * Some PHYs react badly if SStatus is pounded
3894 * immediately after resuming. Delay 200ms before
3895 * debouncing.
3896 */
3897 if (!(link->flags & ATA_LFLAG_NO_DB_DELAY))
3898 ata_msleep(link->ap, 200);
3899
3900 /* is SControl restored correctly? */
3901 if ((rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_CONTROL, &scontrol)))
3902 return rc;
3903 } while ((scontrol & 0xf0f) != 0x300 && --tries);
3904
3905 if ((scontrol & 0xf0f) != 0x300) {
3906 ata_link_warn(link, "failed to resume link (SControl %X)\n",
3907 scontrol);
3908 return 0;
3909 }
3910
3911 if (tries < ATA_LINK_RESUME_TRIES)
3912 ata_link_warn(link, "link resume succeeded after %d retries\n",
3913 ATA_LINK_RESUME_TRIES - tries);
3914
3915 if ((rc = sata_link_debounce(link, params, deadline)))
3916 return rc;
3917
3918 /* clear SError, some PHYs require this even for SRST to work */
3919 if (!(rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_ERROR, &serror)))
3920 rc = sata_scr_write(link, SCR_ERROR, serror);
3921
3922 return rc != -EINVAL ? rc : 0;
3923}
3924
3925/**
3926 * sata_link_scr_lpm - manipulate SControl IPM and SPM fields
3927 * @link: ATA link to manipulate SControl for
3928 * @policy: LPM policy to configure
3929 * @spm_wakeup: initiate LPM transition to active state
3930 *
3931 * Manipulate the IPM field of the SControl register of @link
3932 * according to @policy. If @policy is ATA_LPM_MAX_POWER and
3933 * @spm_wakeup is %true, the SPM field is manipulated to wake up
3934 * the link. This function also clears PHYRDY_CHG before
3935 * returning.
3936 *
3937 * LOCKING:
3938 * EH context.
3939 *
3940 * RETURNS:
3941 * 0 on success, -errno otherwise.
3942 */
3943int sata_link_scr_lpm(struct ata_link *link, enum ata_lpm_policy policy,
3944 bool spm_wakeup)
3945{
3946 struct ata_eh_context *ehc = &link->eh_context;
3947 bool woken_up = false;
3948 u32 scontrol;
3949 int rc;
3950
3951 rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_CONTROL, &scontrol);
3952 if (rc)
3953 return rc;
3954
3955 switch (policy) {
3956 case ATA_LPM_MAX_POWER:
3957 /* disable all LPM transitions */
3958 scontrol |= (0x7 << 8);
3959 /* initiate transition to active state */
3960 if (spm_wakeup) {
3961 scontrol |= (0x4 << 12);
3962 woken_up = true;
3963 }
3964 break;
3965 case ATA_LPM_MED_POWER:
3966 /* allow LPM to PARTIAL */
3967 scontrol &= ~(0x1 << 8);
3968 scontrol |= (0x6 << 8);
3969 break;
3970 case ATA_LPM_MIN_POWER:
3971 if (ata_link_nr_enabled(link) > 0)
3972 /* no restrictions on LPM transitions */
3973 scontrol &= ~(0x7 << 8);
3974 else {
3975 /* empty port, power off */
3976 scontrol &= ~0xf;
3977 scontrol |= (0x1 << 2);
3978 }
3979 break;
3980 default:
3981 WARN_ON(1);
3982 }
3983
3984 rc = sata_scr_write(link, SCR_CONTROL, scontrol);
3985 if (rc)
3986 return rc;
3987
3988 /* give the link time to transit out of LPM state */
3989 if (woken_up)
3990 msleep(10);
3991
3992 /* clear PHYRDY_CHG from SError */
3993 ehc->i.serror &= ~SERR_PHYRDY_CHG;
3994 return sata_scr_write(link, SCR_ERROR, SERR_PHYRDY_CHG);
3995}

3997/**
3998 * ata_std_prereset - prepare for reset
3999 * @link: ATA link to be reset
4000 * @deadline: deadline jiffies for the operation
4001 *
4002 * @link is about to be reset. Initialize it. Failure from
4003 * prereset makes libata abort whole reset sequence and give up
4004 * that port, so prereset should be best-effort. It does its
4005 * best to prepare for reset sequence but if things go wrong, it
4006 * should just whine, not fail.
4007 *
4008 * LOCKING:
4009 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
4010 *
4011 * RETURNS:
4012 * 0 on success, -errno otherwise.
4013 */
4014int ata_std_prereset(struct ata_link *link, unsigned long deadline)
4015{
4016 struct ata_port *ap = link->ap;
4017 struct ata_eh_context *ehc = &link->eh_context;
4018 const unsigned long *timing = sata_ehc_deb_timing(ehc);
4019 int rc;
4020
4021 /* if we're about to do hardreset, nothing more to do */
4022 if (ehc->i.action & ATA_EH_HARDRESET)
4023 return 0;
4024
4025 /* if SATA, resume link */
4026 if (ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_SATA) {
4027 rc = sata_link_resume(link, timing, deadline);
4028 /* whine about phy resume failure but proceed */
4029 if (rc && rc != -EOPNOTSUPP)
4030 ata_link_warn(link,
4031 "failed to resume link for reset (errno=%d)\n",
4032 rc);
4033 }
4034
4035 /* no point in trying softreset on offline link */
4036 if (ata_phys_link_offline(link))
4037 ehc->i.action &= ~ATA_EH_SOFTRESET;
4038
4039 return 0;
4040}

4042/**
4043 * sata_link_hardreset - reset link via SATA phy reset
4044 * @link: link to reset
4045 * @timing: timing parameters { interval, duration, timeout } in msec
4046 * @deadline: deadline jiffies for the operation
4047 * @online: optional out parameter indicating link onlineness
4048 * @check_ready: optional callback to check link readiness
4049 *
4050 * SATA phy-reset @link using DET bits of SControl register.
4051 * After hardreset, link readiness is waited upon using
4052 * ata_wait_ready() if @check_ready is specified. LLDs are
4053 * allowed to not specify @check_ready and wait itself after this
4054 * function returns. Device classification is LLD's
4055 * responsibility.
4056 *
4057 * *@online is set to one iff reset succeeded and @link is online
4058 * after reset.
4059 *
4060 * LOCKING:
4061 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
4062 *
4063 * RETURNS:
4064 * 0 on success, -errno otherwise.
4065 */
4066int sata_link_hardreset(struct ata_link *link, const unsigned long *timing,
4067 unsigned long deadline,
4068 bool *online, int (*check_ready)(struct ata_link *))
4069{
4070 u32 scontrol;
4071 int rc;
4072
4073 DPRINTK("ENTER\n");
4074
4075 if (online)
4076 *online = false;
4077
4078 if (sata_set_spd_needed(link)) {
4079 /* SATA spec says nothing about how to reconfigure
4080 * spd. To be on the safe side, turn off phy during
4081 * reconfiguration. This works for at least ICH7 AHCI
4082 * and Sil3124.
4083 */
4084 if ((rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_CONTROL, &scontrol)))
4085 goto out;
4086
4087 scontrol = (scontrol & 0x0f0) | 0x304;
4088
4089 if ((rc = sata_scr_write(link, SCR_CONTROL, scontrol)))
4090 goto out;
4091
4092 sata_set_spd(link);
4093 }
4094
4095 /* issue phy wake/reset */
4096 if ((rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_CONTROL, &scontrol)))
4097 goto out;
4098
4099 scontrol = (scontrol & 0x0f0) | 0x301;
4100
4101 if ((rc = sata_scr_write_flush(link, SCR_CONTROL, scontrol)))
4102 goto out;
4103
4104 /* Couldn't find anything in SATA I/II specs, but AHCI-1.1
4105 * 10.4.2 says at least 1 ms.
4106 */
4107 ata_msleep(link->ap, 1);
4108
4109 /* bring link back */
4110 rc = sata_link_resume(link, timing, deadline);
4111 if (rc)
4112 goto out;
4113 /* if link is offline nothing more to do */
4114 if (ata_phys_link_offline(link))
4115 goto out;
4116
4117 /* Link is online. From this point, -ENODEV too is an error. */
4118 if (online)
4119 *online = true;
4120
4121 if (sata_pmp_supported(link->ap) && ata_is_host_link(link)) {
4122 /* If PMP is supported, we have to do follow-up SRST.
4123 * Some PMPs don't send D2H Reg FIS after hardreset if
4124 * the first port is empty. Wait only for
4125 * ATA_TMOUT_PMP_SRST_WAIT.
4126 */
4127 if (check_ready) {
4128 unsigned long pmp_deadline;
4129
4130 pmp_deadline = ata_deadline(jiffies,
4131 ATA_TMOUT_PMP_SRST_WAIT);
4132 if (time_after(pmp_deadline, deadline))
4133 pmp_deadline = deadline;
4134 ata_wait_ready(link, pmp_deadline, check_ready);
4135 }
4136 rc = -EAGAIN;
4137 goto out;
4138 }
4139
4140 rc = 0;
4141 if (check_ready)
4142 rc = ata_wait_ready(link, deadline, check_ready);
4143 out:
4144 if (rc && rc != -EAGAIN) {
4145 /* online is set iff link is online && reset succeeded */
4146 if (online)
4147 *online = false;
4148 ata_link_err(link, "COMRESET failed (errno=%d)\n", rc);
4149 }
4150 DPRINTK("EXIT, rc=%d\n", rc);
4151 return rc;
4152}

4154/**
4155 * sata_std_hardreset - COMRESET w/o waiting or classification
4156 * @link: link to reset
4157 * @class: resulting class of attached device
4158 * @deadline: deadline jiffies for the operation
4159 *
4160 * Standard SATA COMRESET w/o waiting or classification.
4161 *
4162 * LOCKING:
4163 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
4164 *
4165 * RETURNS:
4166 * 0 if link offline, -EAGAIN if link online, -errno on errors.
4167 */
4168int sata_std_hardreset(struct ata_link *link, unsigned int *class,
4169 unsigned long deadline)
4170{
4171 const unsigned long *timing = sata_ehc_deb_timing(&link->eh_context);
4172 bool online;
4173 int rc;
4174
4175 /* do hardreset */
4176 rc = sata_link_hardreset(link, timing, deadline, &online, NULL);
4177 return online ? -EAGAIN : rc;
4178}

4181 * ata_std_postreset - standard postreset callback
4182 * @link: the target ata_link
4183 * @classes: classes of attached devices
4184 *
4185 * This function is invoked after a successful reset. Note that
4186 * the device might have been reset more than once using
4187 * different reset methods before postreset is invoked.

4189 * LOCKING:
4190 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)

4208/**
4209 * ata_dev_same_device - Determine whether new ID matches configured device
4210 * @dev: device to compare against
4211 * @new_class: class of the new device
4212 * @new_id: IDENTIFY page of the new device
4213 *
4214 * Compare @new_class and @new_id against @dev and determine
4215 * whether @dev is the device indicated by @new_class and
4216 * @new_id.
4217 *
4218 * LOCKING:
4219 * None.
4220 *
4221 * RETURNS:
4222 * 1 if @dev matches @new_class and @new_id, 0 otherwise.
4223 */
4224static int ata_dev_same_device(struct ata_device *dev, unsigned int new_class,
4225 const u16 *new_id)
4226{
4227 const u16 *old_id = dev->id;
4228 unsigned char model[2][ATA_ID_PROD_LEN + 1];
4229 unsigned char serial[2][ATA_ID_SERNO_LEN + 1];
4230
4231 if (dev->class != new_class) {
4232 ata_dev_info(dev, "class mismatch %d != %d\n",
4233 dev->class, new_class);
4234 return 0;
4235 }
4236
4237 ata_id_c_string(old_id, model[0], ATA_ID_PROD, sizeof(model[0]));
4238 ata_id_c_string(new_id, model[1], ATA_ID_PROD, sizeof(model[1]));
4239 ata_id_c_string(old_id, serial[0], ATA_ID_SERNO, sizeof(serial[0]));
4240 ata_id_c_string(new_id, serial[1], ATA_ID_SERNO, sizeof(serial[1]));
4241
4242 if (strcmp(model[0], model[1])) {
4243 ata_dev_info(dev, "model number mismatch '%s' != '%s'\n",
4244 model[0], model[1]);
4245 return 0;
4246 }
4247
4248 if (strcmp(serial[0], serial[1])) {
4249 ata_dev_info(dev, "serial number mismatch '%s' != '%s'\n",
4250 serial[0], serial[1]);
4251 return 0;
4252 }
4253
4254 return 1;
4255}

4257/**
4258 * ata_dev_reread_id - Re-read IDENTIFY data
4259 * @dev: target ATA device
4260 * @readid_flags: read ID flags
4261 *
4262 * Re-read IDENTIFY page and make sure @dev is still attached to
4263 * the port.
4264 *
4265 * LOCKING:
4266 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
4267 *
4268 * RETURNS:
4269 * 0 on success, negative errno otherwise
4270 */
4271int ata_dev_reread_id(struct ata_device *dev, unsigned int readid_flags)
4272{
4273 unsigned int class = dev->class;
4274 u16 *id = (void *)dev->link->ap->sector_buf;
4275 int rc;
4276
4277 /* read ID data */
4278 rc = ata_dev_read_id(dev, &class, readid_flags, id);
4279 if (rc)
4280 return rc;
4281
4282 /* is the device still there? */
4283 if (!ata_dev_same_device(dev, class, id))
4284 return -ENODEV;
4285
4286 memcpy(dev->id, id, sizeof(id[0]) * ATA_ID_WORDS);
4287 return 0;
4288}

4290/**
4291 * ata_dev_revalidate - Revalidate ATA device
4292 * @dev: device to revalidate
4293 * @new_class: new class code
4294 * @readid_flags: read ID flags
4295 *
4296 * Re-read IDENTIFY page, make sure @dev is still attached to the
4297 * port and reconfigure it according to the new IDENTIFY page.
4298 *
4299 * LOCKING:
4300 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
4301 *
4302 * RETURNS:
4303 * 0 on success, negative errno otherwise
4304 */
4305int ata_dev_revalidate(struct ata_device *dev, unsigned int new_class,
4306 unsigned int readid_flags)
4307{
4308 u64 n_sectors = dev->n_sectors;
4309 u64 n_native_sectors = dev->n_native_sectors;
4310 int rc;
4311
4312 if (!ata_dev_enabled(dev))
4313 return -ENODEV;
4314
4315 /* fail early if !ATA && !ATAPI to avoid issuing [P]IDENTIFY to PMP */
4316 if (ata_class_enabled(new_class) &&
4317 new_class != ATA_DEV_ATA &&
4318 new_class != ATA_DEV_ATAPI &&
4319 new_class != ATA_DEV_ZAC &&
4320 new_class != ATA_DEV_SEMB) {
4321 ata_dev_info(dev, "class mismatch %u != %u\n",
4322 dev->class, new_class);
4323 rc = -ENODEV;
4324 goto fail;
4325 }
4326
4327 /* re-read ID */
4328 rc = ata_dev_reread_id(dev, readid_flags);
4329 if (rc)
4330 goto fail;
4331
4332 /* configure device according to the new ID */
4333 rc = ata_dev_configure(dev);
4334 if (rc)
4335 goto fail;
4336
4337 /* verify n_sectors hasn't changed */
4338 if (dev->class != ATA_DEV_ATA || !n_sectors ||
4339 dev->n_sectors == n_sectors)
4340 return 0;
4341
4342 /* n_sectors has changed */
4343 ata_dev_warn(dev, "n_sectors mismatch %llu != %llu\n",
4344 (unsigned long long)n_sectors,
4345 (unsigned long long)dev->n_sectors);
4346
4347 /*
4348 * Something could have caused HPA to be unlocked
4349 * involuntarily. If n_native_sectors hasn't changed and the
4350 * new size matches it, keep the device.
4351 */
4352 if (dev->n_native_sectors == n_native_sectors &&
4353 dev->n_sectors > n_sectors && dev->n_sectors == n_native_sectors) {
4354 ata_dev_warn(dev,
4355 "new n_sectors matches native, probably "
4356 "late HPA unlock, n_sectors updated\n");
4357 /* use the larger n_sectors */
4358 return 0;
4359 }
4360
4361 /*
4362 * Some BIOSes boot w/o HPA but resume w/ HPA locked. Try
4363 * unlocking HPA in those cases.
4364 *
4365 * https://bugzilla.kernel.org/show_bug.cgi?id=15396
4366 */
4367 if (dev->n_native_sectors == n_native_sectors &&
4368 dev->n_sectors < n_sectors && n_sectors == n_native_sectors &&
4369 !(dev->horkage & ATA_HORKAGE_BROKEN_HPA)) {
4370 ata_dev_warn(dev,
4371 "old n_sectors matches native, probably "
4372 "late HPA lock, will try to unlock HPA\n");
4373 /* try unlocking HPA */
4374 dev->flags |= ATA_DFLAG_UNLOCK_HPA;
4375 rc = -EIO;
4376 } else
4377 rc = -ENODEV;
4378
4379 /* restore original n_[native_]sectors and fail */
4380 dev->n_native_sectors = n_native_sectors;
4381 dev->n_sectors = n_sectors;
4382 fail:
4383 ata_dev_err(dev, "revalidation failed (errno=%d)\n", rc);
4384 return rc;
4385}

4619static unsigned long ata_dev_blacklisted(const struct ata_device *dev)
4620{
4621 unsigned char model_num[ATA_ID_PROD_LEN + 1];
4622 unsigned char model_rev[ATA_ID_FW_REV_LEN + 1];
4623 const struct ata_blacklist_entry *ad = ata_device_blacklist;
4624
4625 ata_id_c_string(dev->id, model_num, ATA_ID_PROD, sizeof(model_num));
4626 ata_id_c_string(dev->id, model_rev, ATA_ID_FW_REV, sizeof(model_rev));
4627
4628 while (ad->model_num) {
4629 if (glob_match(ad->model_num, model_num)) {
4630 if (ad->model_rev == NULL)
4631 return ad->horkage;
4632 if (glob_match(ad->model_rev, model_rev))
4633 return ad->horkage;
4634 }
4635 ad++;
4636 }
4637 return 0;
4638}
4639
4640static int ata_dma_blacklisted(const struct ata_device *dev)
4641{
4642 /* We don't support polling DMA.
4643 * DMA blacklist those ATAPI devices with CDB-intr (and use PIO)
4644 * if the LLDD handles only interrupts in the HSM_ST_LAST state.
4645 */
4646 if ((dev->link->ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_PIO_POLLING) &&
4647 (dev->flags & ATA_DFLAG_CDB_INTR))
4648 return 1;
4649 return (dev->horkage & ATA_HORKAGE_NODMA) ? 1 : 0;
4650}

4652/**
4653 * ata_is_40wire - check drive side detection
4654 * @dev: device
4655 *
4656 * Perform drive side detection decoding, allowing for device vendors
4657 * who can't follow the documentation.
4658 */
4659
4660static int ata_is_40wire(struct ata_device *dev)
4661{
4662 if (dev->horkage & ATA_HORKAGE_IVB)
4663 return ata_drive_40wire_relaxed(dev->id);
4664 return ata_drive_40wire(dev->id);
4665}

4667/**
4668 * cable_is_40wire - 40/80/SATA decider
4669 * @ap: port to consider
4670 *
4671 * This function encapsulates the policy for speed management
4672 * in one place. At the moment we don't cache the result but
4673 * there is a good case for setting ap->cbl to the result when
4674 * we are called with unknown cables (and figuring out if it
4675 * impacts hotplug at all).
4676 *
4677 * Return 1 if the cable appears to be 40 wire.
4678 */
4679
4680static int cable_is_40wire(struct ata_port *ap)
4681{
4682 struct ata_link *link;
4683 struct ata_device *dev;
4684
4685 /* If the controller thinks we are 40 wire, we are. */
4686 if (ap->cbl == ATA_CBL_PATA40)
4687 return 1;
4688
4689 /* If the controller thinks we are 80 wire, we are. */
4690 if (ap->cbl == ATA_CBL_PATA80 || ap->cbl == ATA_CBL_SATA)
4691 return 0;
4692
4693 /* If the system is known to be 40 wire short cable (eg
4694 * laptop), then we allow 80 wire modes even if the drive
4695 * isn't sure.
4696 */
4697 if (ap->cbl == ATA_CBL_PATA40_SHORT)
4698 return 0;
4699
4700 /* If the controller doesn't know, we scan.
4701 *
4702 * Note: We look for all 40 wire detects at this point. Any
4703 * 80 wire detect is taken to be 80 wire cable because
4704 * - in many setups only the one drive (slave if present) will
4705 * give a valid detect
4706 * - if you have a non detect capable drive you don't want it
4707 * to colour the choice
4708 */
4709 ata_for_each_link(link, ap, EDGE) {
4710 ata_for_each_dev(dev, link, ENABLED) {
4711 if (!ata_is_40wire(dev))
4712 return 0;
4713 }
4714 }
4715 return 1;
4716}

4718/**
4719 * ata_dev_xfermask - Compute supported xfermask of the given device
4720 * @dev: Device to compute xfermask for
4721 *
4722 * Compute supported xfermask of @dev and store it in
4723 * dev->*_mask. This function is responsible for applying all
4724 * known limits including host controller limits, device
4725 * blacklist, etc...
4726 *
4727 * LOCKING:
4728 * None.
4729 */
4730static void ata_dev_xfermask(struct ata_device *dev)
4731{
4732 struct ata_link *link = dev->link;
4733 struct ata_port *ap = link->ap;
4734 struct ata_host *host = ap->host;
4735 unsigned long xfer_mask;
4736
4737 /* controller modes available */
4738 xfer_mask = ata_pack_xfermask(ap->pio_mask,
4739 ap->mwdma_mask, ap->udma_mask);
4740
4741 /* drive modes available */
4742 xfer_mask &= ata_pack_xfermask(dev->pio_mask,
4743 dev->mwdma_mask, dev->udma_mask);
4744 xfer_mask &= ata_id_xfermask(dev->id);
4745
4746 /*
4747 * CFA Advanced TrueIDE timings are not allowed on a shared
4748 * cable
4749 */
4750 if (ata_dev_pair(dev)) {
4751 /* No PIO5 or PIO6 */
4752 xfer_mask &= ~(0x03 << (ATA_SHIFT_PIO + 5));
4753 /* No MWDMA3 or MWDMA 4 */
4754 xfer_mask &= ~(0x03 << (ATA_SHIFT_MWDMA + 3));
4755 }
4756
4757 if (ata_dma_blacklisted(dev)) {
4758 xfer_mask &= ~(ATA_MASK_MWDMA | ATA_MASK_UDMA);
4759 ata_dev_warn(dev,
4760 "device is on DMA blacklist, disabling DMA\n");
4761 }
4762
4763 if ((host->flags & ATA_HOST_SIMPLEX) &&
4764 host->simplex_claimed && host->simplex_claimed != ap) {
4765 xfer_mask &= ~(ATA_MASK_MWDMA | ATA_MASK_UDMA);
4766 ata_dev_warn(dev,
4767 "simplex DMA is claimed by other device, disabling DMA\n");
4768 }
4769
4770 if (ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_NO_IORDY)
4771 xfer_mask &= ata_pio_mask_no_iordy(dev);
4772
4773 if (ap->ops->mode_filter)
4774 xfer_mask = ap->ops->mode_filter(dev, xfer_mask);
4775
4776 /* Apply cable rule here. Don't apply it early because when
4777 * we handle hot plug the cable type can itself change.
4778 * Check this last so that we know if the transfer rate was
4779 * solely limited by the cable.
4780 * Unknown or 80 wire cables reported host side are checked
4781 * drive side as well. Cases where we know a 40wire cable
4782 * is used safely for 80 are not checked here.
4783 */
4784 if (xfer_mask & (0xF8 << ATA_SHIFT_UDMA))
4785 /* UDMA/44 or higher would be available */
4786 if (cable_is_40wire(ap)) {
4787 ata_dev_warn(dev,
4788 "limited to UDMA/33 due to 40-wire cable\n");
4789 xfer_mask &= ~(0xF8 << ATA_SHIFT_UDMA);
4790 }
4791
4792 ata_unpack_xfermask(xfer_mask, &dev->pio_mask,
4793 &dev->mwdma_mask, &dev->udma_mask);
4794}

4796/**
4797 * ata_dev_set_xfermode - Issue SET FEATURES - XFER MODE command
4798 * @dev: Device to which command will be sent
4799 *
4800 * Issue SET FEATURES - XFER MODE command to device @dev
4801 * on port @ap.
4802 *
4803 * LOCKING:
4804 * PCI/etc. bus probe sem.
4805 *
4806 * RETURNS:
4807 * 0 on success, AC_ERR_* mask otherwise.
4808 */
4809
4810static unsigned int ata_dev_set_xfermode(struct ata_device *dev)
4811{
4812 struct ata_taskfile tf;
4813 unsigned int err_mask;
4814
4815 /* set up set-features taskfile */
4816 DPRINTK("set features - xfer mode\n");
4817
4818 /* Some controllers and ATAPI devices show flaky interrupt
4819 * behavior after setting xfer mode. Use polling instead.
4820 */
4821 ata_tf_init(dev, &tf);
4822 tf.command = ATA_CMD_SET_FEATURES;
4823 tf.feature = SETFEATURES_XFER;
4824 tf.flags |= ATA_TFLAG_ISADDR | ATA_TFLAG_DEVICE | ATA_TFLAG_POLLING;
4825 tf.protocol = ATA_PROT_NODATA;
4826 /* If we are using IORDY we must send the mode setting command */
4827 if (ata_pio_need_iordy(dev))
4828 tf.nsect = dev->xfer_mode;
4829 /* If the device has IORDY and the controller does not - turn it off */
4830 else if (ata_id_has_iordy(dev->id))
4831 tf.nsect = 0x01;
4832 else /* In the ancient relic department - skip all of this */
4833 return 0;
4834
4835 /* On some disks, this command causes spin-up, so we need longer timeout */
4836 err_mask = ata_exec_internal(dev, &tf, NULL, DMA_NONE, NULL, 0, 15000);
4837
4838 DPRINTK("EXIT, err_mask=%x\n", err_mask);
4839 return err_mask;
4840}

4842/**
4843 * ata_dev_set_feature - Issue SET FEATURES - SATA FEATURES
4844 * @dev: Device to which command will be sent
4845 * @enable: Whether to enable or disable the feature
4846 * @feature: The sector count represents the feature to set
4847 *
4848 * Issue SET FEATURES - SATA FEATURES command to device @dev
4849 * on port @ap with sector count
4850 *
4851 * LOCKING:
4852 * PCI/etc. bus probe sem.
4853 *
4854 * RETURNS:
4855 * 0 on success, AC_ERR_* mask otherwise.
4856 */
4857unsigned int ata_dev_set_feature(struct ata_device *dev, u8 enable, u8 feature)
4858{
4859 struct ata_taskfile tf;
4860 unsigned int err_mask;
4861 unsigned long timeout = 0;
4862
4863 /* set up set-features taskfile */
4864 DPRINTK("set features - SATA features\n");
4865
4866 ata_tf_init(dev, &tf);
4867 tf.command = ATA_CMD_SET_FEATURES;
4868 tf.feature = enable;
4869 tf.flags |= ATA_TFLAG_ISADDR | ATA_TFLAG_DEVICE;
4870 tf.protocol = ATA_PROT_NODATA;
4871 tf.nsect = feature;
4872
4873 if (enable == SETFEATURES_SPINUP)
4874 timeout = ata_probe_timeout ?
4875 ata_probe_timeout * 1000 : SETFEATURES_SPINUP_TIMEOUT;
4876 err_mask = ata_exec_internal(dev, &tf, NULL, DMA_NONE, NULL, 0, timeout);

4878 DPRINTK("EXIT, err_mask=%x\n", err_mask);
4879 return err_mask;
4880}

4883/**
4884 * ata_dev_init_params - Issue INIT DEV PARAMS command
4885 * @dev: Device to which command will be sent
4886 * @heads: Number of heads (taskfile parameter)
4887 * @sectors: Number of sectors (taskfile parameter)
4888 *
4889 * LOCKING:
4890 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
4891 *
4892 * RETURNS:
4893 * 0 on success, AC_ERR_* mask otherwise.
4894 */
4895static unsigned int ata_dev_init_params(struct ata_device *dev,
4896 u16 heads, u16 sectors)
4897{
4898 struct ata_taskfile tf;
4899 unsigned int err_mask;
4900
4901 /* Number of sectors per track 1-255. Number of heads 1-16 */
4902 if (sectors < 1 || sectors > 255 || heads < 1 || heads > 16)
4903 return AC_ERR_INVALID;
4904
4905 /* set up init dev params taskfile */
4906 DPRINTK("init dev params \n");
4907
4908 ata_tf_init(dev, &tf);
4909 tf.command = ATA_CMD_INIT_DEV_PARAMS;
4910 tf.flags |= ATA_TFLAG_ISADDR | ATA_TFLAG_DEVICE;
4911 tf.protocol = ATA_PROT_NODATA;
4912 tf.nsect = sectors;
4913 tf.device |= (heads - 1) & 0x0f; /* max head = num. of heads - 1 */
4914
4915 err_mask = ata_exec_internal(dev, &tf, NULL, DMA_NONE, NULL, 0, 0);
4916 /* A clean abort indicates an original or just out of spec drive
4917 and we should continue as we issue the setup based on the
4918 drive reported working geometry */
4919 if (err_mask == AC_ERR_DEV && (tf.feature & ATA_ABORTED))
4920 err_mask = 0;
4921
4922 DPRINTK("EXIT, err_mask=%x\n", err_mask);
4923 return err_mask;
4924}

4926/**
4927 * atapi_check_dma - Check whether ATAPI DMA can be supported
4928 * @qc: Metadata associated with taskfile to check
4929 *
4930 * Allow low-level driver to filter ATA PACKET commands, returning
4931 * a status indicating whether or not it is OK to use DMA for the
4932 * supplied PACKET command.
4933 *
4934 * LOCKING:
4935 * spin_lock_irqsave(host lock)
4936 *
4937 * RETURNS: 0 when ATAPI DMA can be used
4938 * nonzero otherwise
4939 */
4940int atapi_check_dma(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
4941{
4942 struct ata_port *ap = qc->ap;
4943
4944 /* Don't allow DMA if it isn't multiple of 16 bytes. Quite a
4945 * few ATAPI devices choke on such DMA requests.
4946 */
4947 if (!(qc->dev->horkage & ATA_HORKAGE_ATAPI_MOD16_DMA) &&
4948 unlikely(qc->nbytes & 15))
4949 return 1;
4950
4951 if (ap->ops->check_atapi_dma)
4952 return ap->ops->check_atapi_dma(qc);
4953
4954 return 0;
4955}

4957/**
4958 * ata_std_qc_defer - Check whether a qc needs to be deferred
4959 * @qc: ATA command in question
4960 *
4961 * Non-NCQ commands cannot run with any other command, NCQ or
4962 * not. As upper layer only knows the queue depth, we are
4963 * responsible for maintaining exclusion. This function checks
4964 * whether a new command @qc can be issued.
4965 *
4966 * LOCKING:
4967 * spin_lock_irqsave(host lock)
4968 *
4969 * RETURNS:
4970 * ATA_DEFER_* if deferring is needed, 0 otherwise.
4971 */
4972int ata_std_qc_defer(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
4973{
4974 struct ata_link *link = qc->dev->link;
4975
4976 if (ata_is_ncq(qc->tf.protocol)) {
4977 if (!ata_tag_valid(link->active_tag))
4978 return 0;
4979 } else {
4980 if (!ata_tag_valid(link->active_tag) && !link->sactive)
4981 return 0;
4982 }
4983
4984 return ATA_DEFER_LINK;
4985}

5044 * LOCKING:
5045 * spin_lock_irqsave(host lock)
5046 *
5047 * RETURNS:
5048 * Zero on success, negative on error.
5049 *
5050 */
5051static int ata_sg_setup(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
5052{
5053 struct ata_port *ap = qc->ap;
5054 unsigned int n_elem;
5055
5056 VPRINTK("ENTER, ata%u\n", ap->print_id);
5057
5058 n_elem = dma_map_sg(ap->dev, qc->sg, qc->n_elem, qc->dma_dir);
5059 if (n_elem < 1)
5060 return -1;
5061
5062 DPRINTK("%d sg elements mapped\n", n_elem);
5063 qc->orig_n_elem = qc->n_elem;
5064 qc->n_elem = n_elem;
5065 qc->flags |= ATA_QCFLAG_DMAMAP;
5066
5067 return 0;
5068}
5069
5070#else /* !CONFIG_HAS_DMA */
5071
5072static inline void ata_sg_clean(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc) {}
5073static inline int ata_sg_setup(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc) { return -1; }
5074
5075#endif /* !CONFIG_HAS_DMA */

5077/**
5078 * swap_buf_le16 - swap halves of 16-bit words in place
5079 * @buf: Buffer to swap
5080 * @buf_words: Number of 16-bit words in buffer.
5081 *
5082 * Swap halves of 16-bit words if needed to convert from
5083 * little-endian byte order to native cpu byte order, or
5084 * vice-versa.
5085 *
5086 * LOCKING:
5087 * Inherited from caller.
5088 */
5089void swap_buf_le16(u16 *buf, unsigned int buf_words)
5090{
5091#ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN
5092 unsigned int i;
5093
5094 for (i = 0; i < buf_words; i++)
5095 buf[i] = le16_to_cpu(buf[i]);
5096#endif /* __BIG_ENDIAN */
5097}

5099/**
5100 * ata_qc_new_init - Request an available ATA command, and initialize it
5101 * @dev: Device from whom we request an available command structure
5102 * @tag: tag
5103 *
5104 * LOCKING:
5105 * None.
5106 */
5107
5108struct ata_queued_cmd *ata_qc_new_init(struct ata_device *dev, int tag)
5109{
5110 struct ata_port *ap = dev->link->ap;
5111 struct ata_queued_cmd *qc;
5112
5113 /* no command while frozen */
5114 if (unlikely(ap->pflags & ATA_PFLAG_FROZEN))
5115 return NULL;
5116
5117 /* libsas case */
5118 if (ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_SAS_HOST) {
5119 tag = ata_sas_allocate_tag(ap);
5120 if (tag < 0)
5121 return NULL;
5122 }
5123
5124 qc = __ata_qc_from_tag(ap, tag);
5125 qc->tag = tag;
5126 qc->scsicmd = NULL;
5127 qc->ap = ap;
5128 qc->dev = dev;
5129
5130 ata_qc_reinit(qc);
5131
5132 return qc;
5133}

5135/**
5136 * ata_qc_free - free unused ata_queued_cmd
5137 * @qc: Command to complete
5138 *
5139 * Designed to free unused ata_queued_cmd object
5140 * in case something prevents using it.
5141 *
5142 * LOCKING:
5143 * spin_lock_irqsave(host lock)
5144 */
5145void ata_qc_free(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
5146{
5147 struct ata_port *ap;
5148 unsigned int tag;
5149
5150 WARN_ON_ONCE(qc == NULL); /* ata_qc_from_tag _might_ return NULL */
5151 ap = qc->ap;
5152
5153 qc->flags = 0;
5154 tag = qc->tag;
5155 if (likely(ata_tag_valid(tag))) {
5156 qc->tag = ATA_TAG_POISON;
5157 if (ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_SAS_HOST)
5158 ata_sas_free_tag(tag, ap);
5159 }
5160}
5161
5162void __ata_qc_complete(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
5163{
5164 struct ata_port *ap;
5165 struct ata_link *link;
5166
5167 WARN_ON_ONCE(qc == NULL); /* ata_qc_from_tag _might_ return NULL */
5168 WARN_ON_ONCE(!(qc->flags & ATA_QCFLAG_ACTIVE));
5169 ap = qc->ap;
5170 link = qc->dev->link;
5171
5172 if (likely(qc->flags & ATA_QCFLAG_DMAMAP))
5173 ata_sg_clean(qc);
5174
5175 /* command should be marked inactive atomically with qc completion */
5176 if (ata_is_ncq(qc->tf.protocol)) {
5177 link->sactive &= ~(1 << qc->tag);
5178 if (!link->sactive)
5179 ap->nr_active_links--;
5180 } else {
5181 link->active_tag = ATA_TAG_POISON;
5182 ap->nr_active_links--;
5183 }
5184
5185 /* clear exclusive status */
5186 if (unlikely(qc->flags & ATA_QCFLAG_CLEAR_EXCL &&
5187 ap->excl_link == link))
5188 ap->excl_link = NULL;
5189
5190 /* atapi: mark qc as inactive to prevent the interrupt handler
5191 * from completing the command twice later, before the error handler
5192 * is called. (when rc != 0 and atapi request sense is needed)
5193 */
5194 qc->flags &= ~ATA_QCFLAG_ACTIVE;
5195 ap->qc_active &= ~(1 << qc->tag);
5196
5197 /* call completion callback */
5198 qc->complete_fn(qc);
5199}
5200
5201static void fill_result_tf(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
5202{
5203 struct ata_port *ap = qc->ap;
5204
5205 qc->result_tf.flags = qc->tf.flags;
5206 ap->ops->qc_fill_rtf(qc);
5207}
5208
5209static void ata_verify_xfer(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
5210{
5211 struct ata_device *dev = qc->dev;
5212
5213 if (!ata_is_data(qc->tf.protocol))
5214 return;
5215
5216 if ((dev->mwdma_mask || dev->udma_mask) && ata_is_pio(qc->tf.protocol))
5217 return;
5218
5219 dev->flags &= ~ATA_DFLAG_DUBIOUS_XFER;
5220}

5222/**
5223 * ata_qc_complete - Complete an active ATA command
5224 * @qc: Command to complete
5225 *
5226 * Indicate to the mid and upper layers that an ATA command has
5227 * completed, with either an ok or not-ok status.
5228 *
5229 * Refrain from calling this function multiple times when
5230 * successfully completing multiple NCQ commands.
5231 * ata_qc_complete_multiple() should be used instead, which will
5232 * properly update IRQ expect state.
5233 *
5234 * LOCKING:
5235 * spin_lock_irqsave(host lock)
5236 */
5237void ata_qc_complete(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
5238{
5239 struct ata_port *ap = qc->ap;
5240
5241 /* Trigger the LED (if available) */
5242 ledtrig_disk_activity();
5243
5244 /* XXX: New EH and old EH use different mechanisms to
5245 * synchronize EH with regular execution path.
5246 *
5247 * In new EH, a failed qc is marked with ATA_QCFLAG_FAILED.
5248 * Normal execution path is responsible for not accessing a
5249 * failed qc. libata core enforces the rule by returning NULL
5250 * from ata_qc_from_tag() for failed qcs.
5251 *
5252 * Old EH depends on ata_qc_complete() nullifying completion
5253 * requests if ATA_QCFLAG_EH_SCHEDULED is set. Old EH does
5254 * not synchronize with interrupt handler. Only PIO task is
5255 * taken care of.
5256 */
5257 if (ap->ops->error_handler) {
5258 struct ata_device *dev = qc->dev;
5259 struct ata_eh_info *ehi = &dev->link->eh_info;
5260
5261 if (unlikely(qc->err_mask))
5262 qc->flags |= ATA_QCFLAG_FAILED;
5263
5264 /*
5265 * Finish internal commands without any further processing
5266 * and always with the result TF filled.
5267 */
5268 if (unlikely(ata_tag_internal(qc->tag))) {
5269 fill_result_tf(qc);
5270 trace_ata_qc_complete_internal(qc);
5271 __ata_qc_complete(qc);
5272 return;
5273 }
5274
5275 /*
5276 * Non-internal qc has failed. Fill the result TF and
5277 * summon EH.
5278 */
5279 if (unlikely(qc->flags & ATA_QCFLAG_FAILED)) {
5280 fill_result_tf(qc);
5281 trace_ata_qc_complete_failed(qc);
5282 ata_qc_schedule_eh(qc);
5283 return;
5284 }
5285
5286 WARN_ON_ONCE(ap->pflags & ATA_PFLAG_FROZEN);
5287
5288 /* read result TF if requested */
5289 if (qc->flags & ATA_QCFLAG_RESULT_TF)
5290 fill_result_tf(qc);
5291
5292 trace_ata_qc_complete_done(qc);
5293 /* Some commands need post-processing after successful
5294 * completion.
5295 */
5296 switch (qc->tf.command) {
5297 case ATA_CMD_SET_FEATURES:
5298 if (qc->tf.feature != SETFEATURES_WC_ON &&
5299 qc->tf.feature != SETFEATURES_WC_OFF &&
5300 qc->tf.feature != SETFEATURES_RA_ON &&
5301 qc->tf.feature != SETFEATURES_RA_OFF)
5302 break;
5303 /* fall through */
5304 case ATA_CMD_INIT_DEV_PARAMS: /* CHS translation changed */
5305 case ATA_CMD_SET_MULTI: /* multi_count changed */
5306 /* revalidate device */
5307 ehi->dev_action[dev->devno] |= ATA_EH_REVALIDATE;
5308 ata_port_schedule_eh(ap);
5309 break;
5310
5311 case ATA_CMD_SLEEP:
5312 dev->flags |= ATA_DFLAG_SLEEPING;
5313 break;
5314 }
5315
5316 if (unlikely(dev->flags & ATA_DFLAG_DUBIOUS_XFER))
5317 ata_verify_xfer(qc);
5318
5319 __ata_qc_complete(qc);
5320 } else {
5321 if (qc->flags & ATA_QCFLAG_EH_SCHEDULED)
5322 return;
5323
5324 /* read result TF if failed or requested */
5325 if (qc->err_mask || qc->flags & ATA_QCFLAG_RESULT_TF)
5326 fill_result_tf(qc);
5327
5328 __ata_qc_complete(qc);
5329 }
5330}
5331
5332/**
5333 * ata_qc_complete_multiple - Complete multiple qcs successfully
5334 * @ap: port in question
5335 * @qc_active: new qc_active mask
5336 *
5337 * Complete in-flight commands. This functions is meant to be
5338 * called from low-level driver's interrupt routine to complete
5339 * requests normally. ap->qc_active and @qc_active is compared
5340 * and commands are completed accordingly.
5341 *
5342 * Always use this function when completing multiple NCQ commands
5343 * from IRQ handlers instead of calling ata_qc_complete()
5344 * multiple times to keep IRQ expect status properly in sync.
5345 *
5346 * LOCKING:
5347 * spin_lock_irqsave(host lock)
5348 *
5349 * RETURNS:
5350 * Number of completed commands on success, -errno otherwise.
5351 */
5352int ata_qc_complete_multiple(struct ata_port *ap, u32 qc_active)
5353{
5354 int nr_done = 0;
5355 u32 done_mask;
5356
5357 done_mask = ap->qc_active ^ qc_active;
5358
5359 if (unlikely(done_mask & qc_active)) {
5360 ata_port_err(ap, "illegal qc_active transition (%08x->%08x)\n",
5361 ap->qc_active, qc_active);
5362 return -EINVAL;
5363 }
5364
5365 while (done_mask) {
5366 struct ata_queued_cmd *qc;
5367 unsigned int tag = __ffs(done_mask);
5368
5369 qc = ata_qc_from_tag(ap, tag);
5370 if (qc) {
5371 ata_qc_complete(qc);
5372 nr_done++;
5373 }
5374 done_mask &= ~(1 << tag);
5375 }
5376
5377 return nr_done;
5378}

5380/**
5381 * ata_qc_issue - issue taskfile to device
5382 * @qc: command to issue to device
5383 *
5384 * Prepare an ATA command to submission to device.
5385 * This includes mapping the data into a DMA-able
5386 * area, filling in the S/G table, and finally
5387 * writing the taskfile to hardware, starting the command.
5388 *
5389 * LOCKING:
5390 * spin_lock_irqsave(host lock)
5391 */
5392void ata_qc_issue(struct ata_queued_cmd *qc)
5393{
5394 struct ata_port *ap = qc->ap;
5395 struct ata_link *link = qc->dev->link;
5396 u8 prot = qc->tf.protocol;
5397
5398 /* Make sure only one non-NCQ command is outstanding. The
5399 * check is skipped for old EH because it reuses active qc to
5400 * request ATAPI sense.
5401 */
5402 WARN_ON_ONCE(ap->ops->error_handler && ata_tag_valid(link->active_tag));
5403
5404 if (ata_is_ncq(prot)) {
5405 WARN_ON_ONCE(link->sactive & (1 << qc->tag));
5406
5407 if (!link->sactive)
5408 ap->nr_active_links++;
5409 link->sactive |= 1 << qc->tag;
5410 } else {
5411 WARN_ON_ONCE(link->sactive);
5412
5413 ap->nr_active_links++;
5414 link->active_tag = qc->tag;
5415 }
5416
5417 qc->flags |= ATA_QCFLAG_ACTIVE;
5418 ap->qc_active |= 1 << qc->tag;
5419
5420 /*
5421 * We guarantee to LLDs that they will have at least one
5422 * non-zero sg if the command is a data command.
5423 */
5424 if (ata_is_data(prot) && (!qc->sg || !qc->n_elem || !qc->nbytes))
5425 goto sys_err;
5426
5427 if (ata_is_dma(prot) || (ata_is_pio(prot) &&
5428 (ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_PIO_DMA)))
5429 if (ata_sg_setup(qc))
5430 goto sys_err;
5431
5432 /* if device is sleeping, schedule reset and abort the link */
5433 if (unlikely(qc->dev->flags & ATA_DFLAG_SLEEPING)) {
5434 link->eh_info.action |= ATA_EH_RESET;
5435 ata_ehi_push_desc(&link->eh_info, "waking up from sleep");
5436 ata_link_abort(link);
5437 return;
5438 }
5439
5440 ap->ops->qc_prep(qc);
5441 trace_ata_qc_issue(qc);
5442 qc->err_mask |= ap->ops->qc_issue(qc);
5443 if (unlikely(qc->err_mask))
5444 goto err;
5445 return;
5446
5447sys_err:
5448 qc->err_mask |= AC_ERR_SYSTEM;
5449err:
5450 ata_qc_complete(qc);
5451}

5474 * @link: ATA link to read SCR for
5475 * @reg: SCR to read
5476 * @val: Place to store read value
5477 *
5478 * Read SCR register @reg of @link into *@val. This function is
5479 * guaranteed to succeed if @link is ap->link, the cable type of
5480 * the port is SATA and the port implements ->scr_read.

5491 if (sata_scr_valid(link))
5492 return link->ap->ops->scr_read(link, reg, val);
5493 return -EOPNOTSUPP;

5495

5499/**
5500 * sata_scr_write - write SCR register of the specified port
5501 * @link: ATA link to write SCR for
5502 * @reg: SCR to write
5503 * @val: value to write
5504 *
5505 * Write @val to SCR register @reg of @link. This function is
5506 * guaranteed to succeed if @link is ap->link, the cable type of
5507 * the port is SATA and the port implements ->scr_read.
5508 *

5510 * None if @link is ap->link. Kernel thread context otherwise.
5511 *
5512 * RETURNS:

5526/**
5527 * sata_scr_write_flush - write SCR register of the specified port and flush
5528 * @link: ATA link to write SCR for
5529 * @reg: SCR to write
5530 * @val: value to write
5531 *
5532 * This function is identical to sata_scr_write() except that this
5533 * function performs flush after writing to the register.
5534 *
5535 * LOCKING:
5536 * None if @link is ap->link. Kernel thread context otherwise.
5537 *
5538 * RETURNS:
5539 * 0 on success, negative errno on failure.
5540 */
5541int sata_scr_write_flush(struct ata_link *link, int reg, u32 val)
5542{

5547 rc = link->ap->ops->scr_write(link, reg, val);
5548 if (rc == 0)
5549 rc = link->ap->ops->scr_read(link, reg, &val);
5550 return rc;
5551 }
5552 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
5553 }
5554
5555 return sata_pmp_scr_write(link, reg, val);
5556}

5558/**
5559 * ata_phys_link_online - test whether the given link is online
5560 * @link: ATA link to test
5561 *
5562 * Test whether @link is online. Note that this function returns
5563 * 0 if online status of @link cannot be obtained, so
5564 * ata_link_online(link) != !ata_link_offline(link).
5565 *
5566 * LOCKING:
5567 * None.
5568 *
5569 * RETURNS:
5570 * True if the port online status is available and online.
5571 */
5572bool ata_phys_link_online(struct ata_link *link)
5573{

5575
5576 if (sata_scr_read(link, SCR_STATUS, &sstatus) == 0 &&

5578 return true;
5579 return false;

5585 *
5586 * Test whether @link is offline. Note that this function
5587 * returns 0 if offline status of @link cannot be obtained, so
5588 * ata_link_online(link) != !ata_link_offline(link).
5589 *
5590 * LOCKING:
5591 * None.
5592 *
5593 * RETURNS:

5596bool ata_phys_link_offline(struct ata_link *link)

5606/**
5607 * ata_link_online - test whether the given link is online
5608 * @link: ATA link to test
5609 *
5610 * Test whether @link is online. This is identical to
5611 * ata_phys_link_online() when there's no slave link. When
5612 * there's a slave link, this function should only be called on
5613 * the master link and will return true if any of M/S links is
5614 * online.
5615 *
5616 * LOCKING:
5617 * None.
5618 *
5619 * RETURNS:
5620 * True if the port online status is available and online.
5621 */
5622bool ata_link_online(struct ata_link *link)
5623{
5624 struct ata_link *slave = link->ap->slave_link;
5625
5626 WARN_ON(link == slave); /* shouldn't be called on slave link */
5627
5628 return ata_phys_link_online(link) ||
5629 (slave && ata_phys_link_online(slave));
5630}

5632/**
5633 * ata_link_offline - test whether the given link is offline
5634 * @link: ATA link to test
5635 *
5636 * Test whether @link is offline. This is identical to
5637 * ata_phys_link_offline() when there's no slave link. When
5638 * there's a slave link, this function should only be called on
5639 * the master link and will return true if both M/S links are
5640 * offline.
5641 *
5642 * LOCKING:
5643 * None.
5644 *
5645 * RETURNS:
5646 * True if the port offline status is available and offline.
5647 */
5648bool ata_link_offline(struct ata_link *link)
5649{
5650 struct ata_link *slave = link->ap->slave_link;
5651
5652 WARN_ON(link == slave); /* shouldn't be called on slave link */
5653
5654 return ata_phys_link_offline(link) &&
5655 (!slave || ata_phys_link_offline(slave));
5656}

5658#ifdef CONFIG_PM
5659static void ata_port_request_pm(struct ata_port *ap, pm_message_t mesg,
5660 unsigned int action, unsigned int ehi_flags,
5661 bool async)
5662{
5663 struct ata_link *link;
5664 unsigned long flags;
5665
5666 /* Previous resume operation might still be in
5667 * progress. Wait for PM_PENDING to clear.
5668 */
5669 if (ap->pflags & ATA_PFLAG_PM_PENDING) {
5670 ata_port_wait_eh(ap);
5671 WARN_ON(ap->pflags & ATA_PFLAG_PM_PENDING);
5672 }
5673
5674 /* request PM ops to EH */
5675 spin_lock_irqsave(ap->lock, flags);
5676
5677 ap->pm_mesg = mesg;
5678 ap->pflags |= ATA_PFLAG_PM_PENDING;
5679 ata_for_each_link(link, ap, HOST_FIRST) {
5680 link->eh_info.action |= action;
5681 link->eh_info.flags |= ehi_flags;
5682 }
5683
5684 ata_port_schedule_eh(ap);
5685
5686 spin_unlock_irqrestore(ap->lock, flags);
5687
5688 if (!async) {
5689 ata_port_wait_eh(ap);
5690 WARN_ON(ap->pflags & ATA_PFLAG_PM_PENDING);
5691 }
5692}
5693
5694/*
5695 * On some hardware, device fails to respond after spun down for suspend. As
5696 * the device won't be used before being resumed, we don't need to touch the
5697 * device. Ask EH to skip the usual stuff and proceed directly to suspend.
5698 *
5699 * http://thread.gmane.org/gmane.linux.ide/46764
5700 */
5701static const unsigned int ata_port_suspend_ehi = ATA_EHI_QUIET
5702 | ATA_EHI_NO_AUTOPSY
5703 | ATA_EHI_NO_RECOVERY;
5704
5705static void ata_port_suspend(struct ata_port *ap, pm_message_t mesg)
5706{
5707 ata_port_request_pm(ap, mesg, 0, ata_port_suspend_ehi, false);
5708}
5709
5710static void ata_port_suspend_async(struct ata_port *ap, pm_message_t mesg)
5711{
5712 ata_port_request_pm(ap, mesg, 0, ata_port_suspend_ehi, true);
5713}
5714
5715static int ata_port_pm_suspend(struct device *dev)
5716{
5717 struct ata_port *ap = to_ata_port(dev);
5718
5719 if (pm_runtime_suspended(dev))
5720 return 0;
5721
5722 ata_port_suspend(ap, PMSG_SUSPEND);
5723 return 0;
5724}
5725
5726static int ata_port_pm_freeze(struct device *dev)
5727{
5728 struct ata_port *ap = to_ata_port(dev);
5729
5730 if (pm_runtime_suspended(dev))
5731 return 0;

5734 return 0;
5735}

5765/*
5766 * For ODDs, the upper layer will poll for media change every few seconds,
5767 * which will make it enter and leave suspend state every few seconds. And
5768 * as each suspend will cause a hard/soft reset, the gain of runtime suspend
5769 * is very little and the ODD may malfunction after constantly being reset.
5770 * So the idle callback here will not proceed to suspend if a non-ZPODD capable
5771 * ODD is attached to the port.
5772 */
5773static int ata_port_runtime_idle(struct device *dev)
5774{
5775 struct ata_port *ap = to_ata_port(dev);
5776 struct ata_link *link;
5777 struct ata_device *adev;
5778
5779 ata_for_each_link(link, ap, HOST_FIRST) {
5780 ata_for_each_dev(adev, link, ENABLED)
5781 if (adev->class == ATA_DEV_ATAPI &&
5782 !zpodd_dev_enabled(adev))
5783 return -EBUSY;
5784 }
5785
5786 return 0;
5787}

5792 return 0;
5793}
5794
5795static int ata_port_runtime_resume(struct device *dev)
5796{
5797 ata_port_resume(to_ata_port(dev), PMSG_AUTO_RESUME);
5798 return 0;
5799}

5865 * @dev: Device structure to initialize
5866 *
5867 * Initialize @dev in preparation for probing.
5868 *
5869 * LOCKING:
5870 * Inherited from caller.
5871 */
5872void ata_dev_init(struct ata_device *dev)
5873{

5892 ATA_DEVICE_CLEAR_END - ATA_DEVICE_CLEAR_BEGIN);
5893 dev->pio_mask = UINT_MAX;
5894 dev->mwdma_mask = UINT_MAX;
5895 dev->udma_mask = UINT_MAX;

5899 * ata_link_init - Initialize an ata_link structure
5900 * @ap: ATA port link is attached to
5901 * @link: Link structure to initialize
5902 * @pmp: Port multiplier port number
5903 *
5904 * Initialize @link.
5905 *
5906 * LOCKING:
5907 * Kernel thread context (may sleep)
5908 */
5909void ata_link_init(struct ata_port *ap, struct ata_link *link, int pmp)
5910{

5912

5914 memset((void *)link + ATA_LINK_CLEAR_BEGIN, 0,

5935/**
5936 * sata_link_init_spd - Initialize link->sata_spd_limit
5937 * @link: Link to configure sata_spd_limit for
5938 *
5939 * Initialize @link->[hw_]sata_spd_limit to the currently
5940 * configured value.
5941 *
5942 * LOCKING:
5943 * Kernel thread context (may sleep).
5944 *
5945 * RETURNS:
5946 * 0 on success, -errno on failure.
5947 */
5948int sata_link_init_spd(struct ata_link *link)
5949{
5950 u8 spd;
5951 int rc;
5952
5953 rc = sata_scr_read(link, SCR_CONTROL, &link->saved_scontrol);
5954 if (rc)
5955 return rc;
5956
5957 spd = (link->saved_scontrol >> 4) & 0xf;
5958 if (spd)
5959 link->hw_sata_spd_limit &= (1 << spd) - 1;
5960
5961 ata_force_link_limits(link);
5962
5963 link->sata_spd_limit = link->hw_sata_spd_limit;
5964
5965 return 0;
5966}

5968/**
5969 * ata_port_alloc - allocate and initialize basic ATA port resources
5970 * @host: ATA host this allocated port belongs to
5971 *
5972 * Allocate and initialize basic ATA port resources.
5973 *
5974 * RETURNS:
5975 * Allocate ATA port on success, NULL on failure.
5976 *
5977 * LOCKING:
5978 * Inherited from calling layer (may sleep).
5979 */
5980struct ata_port *ata_port_alloc(struct ata_host *host)
5981{

5985

6029static void ata_host_release(struct device *gendev, void *res)
6030{
6031 struct ata_host *host = dev_get_drvdata(gendev);
6032 int i;
6033
6034 for (i = 0; i < host->n_ports; i++) {
6035 struct ata_port *ap = host->ports[i];
6036
6037 if (!ap)
6038 continue;
6039
6040 if (ap->scsi_host)
6041 scsi_host_put(ap->scsi_host);
6042
6043 kfree(ap->pmp_link);
6044 kfree(ap->slave_link);
6045 kfree(ap);
6046 host->ports[i] = NULL;
6047 }
6048
6049 dev_set_drvdata(gendev, NULL);
6050}

6052/**
6053 * ata_host_alloc - allocate and init basic ATA host resources
6054 * @dev: generic device this host is associated with
6055 * @max_ports: maximum number of ATA ports associated with this host
6056 *
6057 * Allocate and initialize basic ATA host resources. LLD calls
6058 * this function to allocate a host, initializes it fully and
6059 * attaches it using ata_host_register().
6060 *
6061 * @max_ports ports are allocated and host->n_ports is
6062 * initialized to @max_ports. The caller is allowed to decrease
6063 * host->n_ports before calling ata_host_register(). The unused
6064 * ports will be automatically freed on registration.
6065 *
6066 * RETURNS:
6067 * Allocate ATA host on success, NULL on failure.
6068 *
6069 * LOCKING:
6070 * Inherited from calling layer (may sleep).
6071 */
6072struct ata_host *ata_host_alloc(struct device *dev, int max_ports)
6073{
6074 struct ata_host *host;
6075 size_t sz;
6076 int i;
6077
6078 DPRINTK("ENTER\n");
6079
6080 if (!devres_open_group(dev, NULL, GFP_KERNEL))
6081 return NULL;
6082
6083 /* alloc a container for our list of ATA ports (buses) */
6084 sz = sizeof(struct ata_host) + (max_ports + 1) * sizeof(void *);
6085 /* alloc a container for our list of ATA ports (buses) */
6086 host = devres_alloc(ata_host_release, sz, GFP_KERNEL);
6087 if (!host)
6088 goto err_out;
6089
6090 devres_add(dev, host);
6091 dev_set_drvdata(dev, host);
6092
6093 spin_lock_init(&host->lock);
6094 mutex_init(&host->eh_mutex);
6095 host->dev = dev;
6096 host->n_ports = max_ports;
6097
6098 /* allocate ports bound to this host */
6099 for (i = 0; i < max_ports; i++) {
6100 struct ata_port *ap;
6101
6102 ap = ata_port_alloc(host);
6103 if (!ap)
6104 goto err_out;
6105
6106 ap->port_no = i;
6107 host->ports[i] = ap;
6108 }
6109
6110 devres_remove_group(dev, NULL);
6111 return host;
6112
6113 err_out:
6114 devres_release_group(dev, NULL);
6115 return NULL;
6116}

6118/**
6119 * ata_host_alloc_pinfo - alloc host and init with port_info array
6120 * @dev: generic device this host is associated with
6121 * @ppi: array of ATA port_info to initialize host with
6122 * @n_ports: number of ATA ports attached to this host
6123 *
6124 * Allocate ATA host and initialize with info from @ppi. If NULL
6125 * terminated, @ppi may contain fewer entries than @n_ports. The
6126 * last entry will be used for the remaining ports.
6127 *
6128 * RETURNS:
6129 * Allocate ATA host on success, NULL on failure.
6130 *
6131 * LOCKING:
6132 * Inherited from calling layer (may sleep).
6133 */
6134struct ata_host *ata_host_alloc_pinfo(struct device *dev,
6135 const struct ata_port_info * const * ppi,
6136 int n_ports)
6137{
6138 const struct ata_port_info *pi;
6139 struct ata_host *host;
6140 int i, j;
6141
6142 host = ata_host_alloc(dev, n_ports);
6143 if (!host)
6144 return NULL;
6145
6146 for (i = 0, j = 0, pi = NULL; i < host->n_ports; i++) {
6147 struct ata_port *ap = host->ports[i];
6148
6149 if (ppi[j])
6150 pi = ppi[j++];
6151
6152 ap->pio_mask = pi->pio_mask;
6153 ap->mwdma_mask = pi->mwdma_mask;
6154 ap->udma_mask = pi->udma_mask;
6155 ap->flags |= pi->flags;
6156 ap->link.flags |= pi->link_flags;
6157 ap->ops = pi->port_ops;
6158
6159 if (!host->ops && (pi->port_ops != &ata_dummy_port_ops))
6160 host->ops = pi->port_ops;
6161 }
6162
6163 return host;
6164}

6166/**
6167 * ata_slave_link_init - initialize slave link
6168 * @ap: port to initialize slave link for
6169 *
6170 * Create and initialize slave link for @ap. This enables slave
6171 * link handling on the port.
6172 *
6173 * In libata, a port contains links and a link contains devices.
6174 * There is single host link but if a PMP is attached to it,
6175 * there can be multiple fan-out links. On SATA, there's usually
6176 * a single device connected to a link but PATA and SATA
6177 * controllers emulating TF based interface can have two - master
6178 * and slave.
6179 *
6180 * However, there are a few controllers which don't fit into this
6181 * abstraction too well - SATA controllers which emulate TF
6182 * interface with both master and slave devices but also have
6183 * separate SCR register sets for each device. These controllers
6184 * need separate links for physical link handling
6185 * (e.g. onlineness, link speed) but should be treated like a
6186 * traditional M/S controller for everything else (e.g. command
6187 * issue, softreset).
6188 *
6189 * slave_link is libata's way of handling this class of
6190 * controllers without impacting core layer too much. For
6191 * anything other than physical link handling, the default host
6192 * link is used for both master and slave. For physical link
6193 * handling, separate @ap->slave_link is used. All dirty details
6194 * are implemented inside libata core layer. From LLD's POV, the
6195 * only difference is that prereset, hardreset and postreset are
6196 * called once more for the slave link, so the reset sequence
6197 * looks like the following.
6198 *
6199 * prereset(M) -> prereset(S) -> hardreset(M) -> hardreset(S) ->
6200 * softreset(M) -> postreset(M) -> postreset(S)
6201 *
6202 * Note that softreset is called only for the master. Softreset
6203 * resets both M/S by definition, so SRST on master should handle
6204 * both (the standard method will work just fine).
6205 *
6206 * LOCKING:
6207 * Should be called before host is registered.
6208 *
6209 * RETURNS:
6210 * 0 on success, -errno on failure.
6211 */
6212int ata_slave_link_init(struct ata_port *ap)
6213{
6214 struct ata_link *link;
6215
6216 WARN_ON(ap->slave_link);
6217 WARN_ON(ap->flags & ATA_FLAG_PMP);
6218
6219 link = kzalloc(sizeof(*link), GFP_KERNEL);
6220 if (!link)
6221 return -ENOMEM;
6222
6223 ata_link_init(ap, link, 1);
6224 ap->slave_link = link;
6225 return 0;
6226}

6228static void ata_host_stop(struct device *gendev, void *res)
6229{
6230 struct ata_host *host = dev_get_drvdata(gendev);
6231 int i;
6232
6233 WARN_ON(!(host->flags & ATA_HOST_STARTED));
6234
6235 for (i = 0; i < host->n_ports; i++) {
6236 struct ata_port *ap = host->ports[i];
6237
6238 if (ap->ops->port_stop)
6239 ap->ops->port_stop(ap);
6240 }
6241
6242 if (host->ops->host_stop)
6243 host->ops->host_stop(host);
6244}

6246/**
6247 * ata_finalize_port_ops - finalize ata_port_operations
6248 * @ops: ata_port_operations to finalize
6249 *
6250 * An ata_port_operations can inherit from another ops and that
6251 * ops can again inherit from another. This can go on as many
6252 * times as necessary as long as there is no loop in the
6253 * inheritance chain.
6254 *
6255 * Ops tables are finalized when the host is started. NULL or
6256 * unspecified entries are inherited from the closet ancestor
6257 * which has the method and the entry is populated with it.
6258 * After finalization, the ops table directly points to all the
6259 * methods and ->inherits is no longer necessary and cleared.
6260 *
6261 * Using ATA_OP_NULL, inheriting ops can force a method to NULL.
6262 *
6263 * LOCKING:
6264 * None.
6265 */
6266static void ata_finalize_port_ops(struct ata_port_operations *ops)
6267{
6268 static DEFINE_SPINLOCK(lock);
6269 const struct ata_port_operations *cur;
6270 void **begin = (void **)ops;
6271 void **end = (void **)&ops->inherits;
6272 void **pp;
6273
6274 if (!ops || !ops->inherits)
6275 return;
6276
6277 spin_lock(&lock);
6278
6279 for (cur = ops->inherits; cur; cur = cur->inherits) {
6280 void **inherit = (void **)cur;
6281
6282 for (pp = begin; pp < end; pp++, inherit++)
6283 if (!*pp)
6284 *pp = *inherit;
6285 }
6286
6287 for (pp = begin; pp < end; pp++)
6288 if (IS_ERR(*pp))
6289 *pp = NULL;
6290
6291 ops->inherits = NULL;
6292
6293 spin_unlock(&lock);
6294}

6296/**
6297 * ata_host_start - start and freeze ports of an ATA host
6298 * @host: ATA host to start ports for
6299 *
6300 * Start and then freeze ports of @host. Started status is
6301 * recorded in host->flags, so this function can be called
6302 * multiple times. Ports are guaranteed to get started only
6303 * once. If host->ops isn't initialized yet, its set to the
6304 * first non-dummy port ops.
6305 *
6306 * LOCKING:
6307 * Inherited from calling layer (may sleep).
6308 *
6309 * RETURNS:
6310 * 0 if all ports are started successfully, -errno otherwise.
6311 */
6312int ata_host_start(struct ata_host *host)
6313{
6314 int have_stop = 0;
6315 void *start_dr = NULL;
6316 int i, rc;
6317
6318 if (host->flags & ATA_HOST_STARTED)
6319 return 0;
6320
6321 ata_finalize_port_ops(host->ops);
6322
6323 for (i = 0; i < host->n_ports; i++) {
6324 struct ata_port *ap = host->ports[i];
6325
6326 ata_finalize_port_ops(ap->ops);
6327
6328 if (!host->ops && !ata_port_is_dummy(ap))
6329 host->ops = ap->ops;
6330
6331 if (ap->ops->port_stop)
6332 have_stop = 1;
6333 }
6334
6335 if (host->ops->host_stop)
6336 have_stop = 1;
6337
6338 if (have_stop) {
6339 start_dr = devres_alloc(ata_host_stop, 0, GFP_KERNEL);
6340 if (!start_dr)
6341 return -ENOMEM;
6342 }
6343
6344 for (i = 0; i < host->n_ports; i++) {
6345 struct ata_port *ap = host->ports[i];
6346
6347 if (ap->ops->port_start) {
6348 rc = ap->ops->port_start(ap);
6349 if (rc) {
6350 if (rc != -ENODEV)
6351 dev_err(host->dev,
6352 "failed to start port %d (errno=%d)\n",
6353 i, rc);
6354 goto err_out;
6355 }
6356 }
6357 ata_eh_freeze_port(ap);
6358 }
6359
6360 if (start_dr)
6361 devres_add(host->dev, start_dr);
6362 host->flags |= ATA_HOST_STARTED;
6363 return 0;
6364
6365 err_out:
6366 while (--i >= 0) {
6367 struct ata_port *ap = host->ports[i];
6368
6369 if (ap->ops->port_stop)
6370 ap->ops->port_stop(ap);
6371 }
6372 devres_free(start_dr);
6373 return rc;
6374}

6392
6393void __ata_port_probe(struct ata_port *ap)
6394{
6395 struct ata_eh_info *ehi = &ap->link.eh_info;
6396 unsigned long flags;
6397
6398 /* kick EH for boot probing */
6399 spin_lock_irqsave(ap->lock, flags);
6400
6401 ehi->probe_mask |= ATA_ALL_DEVICES;
6402 ehi->action |= ATA_EH_RESET;
6403 ehi->flags |= ATA_EHI_NO_AUTOPSY | ATA_EHI_QUIET;
6404
6405 ap->pflags &= ~ATA_PFLAG_INITIALIZING;
6406 ap->pflags |= ATA_PFLAG_LOADING;
6407 ata_port_schedule_eh(ap);
6408
6409 spin_unlock_irqrestore(ap->lock, flags);
6410}
6411
6412int ata_port_probe(struct ata_port *ap)
6413{
6414 int rc = 0;
6415
6416 if (ap->ops->error_handler) {
6417 __ata_port_probe(ap);
6418 ata_port_wait_eh(ap);
6419 } else {
6420 DPRINTK("ata%u: bus probe begin\n", ap->print_id);
6421 rc = ata_bus_probe(ap);
6422 DPRINTK("ata%u: bus probe end\n", ap->print_id);
6423 }
6424 return rc;
6425}
6426
6427
6428static void async_port_probe(void *data, async_cookie_t cookie)
6429{
6430 struct ata_port *ap = data;
6431
6432 /*
6433 * If we're not allowed to scan this host in parallel,
6434 * we need to wait until all previous scans have completed
6435 * before going further.
6436 * Jeff Garzik says this is only within a controller, so we
6437 * don't need to wait for port 0, only for later ports.
6438 */
6439 if (!(ap->host->flags & ATA_HOST_PARALLEL_SCAN) && ap->port_no != 0)
6440 async_synchronize_cookie(cookie);
6441
6442 (void)ata_port_probe(ap);
6443
6444 /* in order to keep device order, we need to synchronize at this point */
6445 async_synchronize_cookie(cookie);
6446
6447 ata_scsi_scan_host(ap, 1);
6448}
